14,0,0,"Due to the increase in annual electricity consumption occurring in Portugal and the rising price of fossil fuels, it is imperative to diversificate the energy sources available. The Portuguese investment in renewable energies has increased significantly in the past few years, especially in wind energy. Renewable energies are intermittent and dependent on weather conditions, so fossil fuels are still an important part of the Portuguese energy mix, but with tendency to decrease in the future. In this paper, the nuclear option has been considered alongside the renewable energies increase to reduce fossil fuels dependency, envisaging several plausible scenarios for fuel prices, installed capacity and investment costs. © 2012, European Association for the Development of Renewable Energy, Environment and Power Quality (EA4EPQ). All rights reserved.","['due', 'increase', 'annual', 'electricity', 'consumption', 'occurring', 'portugal', 'rising', 'price', 'fossil', 'fuels', 'imperative', 'diversificate', 'energy', 'sources', 'available', 'portuguese', 'investment', 'renewable', 'energies', 'increased', 'past', 'years', 'wind', 'energy', 'renewable', 'energies', 'intermittent', 'dependent', 'weather', 'conditions', 'fossil', 'fuels', 'important', 'part', 'portuguese', 'energy', 'mix', 'tendency', 'decrease', 'future', 'nuclear', 'option', 'considered', 'renewable', 'energies', 'increase', 'reduce', 'fossil', 'fuels', 'dependency', 'envisaging', 'several', 'plausible', 'scenarios', 'fuel', 'prices', 'installed', 'capacity', 'investment', 'costs', 'european', 'association', 'development', 'renewable', 'energy', 'environment', 'power', 'quality', 'rights_reserved']"
15,0,0,"Heat pump performance is always improving. Lower minimum operating temperatures and better performance curves are increasing both the number of hours of useful service and effectiveness while in use. We estimate the rate of technological development for residential air source heat pumps and their consequent rate of adoption using a system dynamics model. From the perspective of the use stage in life cycle assessment, energy savings and greenhouse gas emissions reductions are estimated. A substantial reduction in overall energy consumption is predicted, while greenhouse gas emissions are only reduced where electricity is generated with little or no fossil fuels. © 2016 The Authors.","['heat', 'pump', 'performance', 'improving', 'lower', 'minimum', 'operating', 'temperatures', 'performance', 'curves', 'increasing', 'number', 'hours', 'useful', 'service', 'effectiveness', 'estimate', 'rate', 'technological', 'development', 'residential', 'air', 'source', 'heat', 'pumps', 'consequent', 'rate', 'adoption', 'system', 'dynamics', 'model', 'perspective', 'stage', 'life', 'cycle', 'assessment', 'energy', 'savings', 'greenhouse', 'gas', 'emissions', 'reductions', 'estimated', 'substantial', 'reduction', 'overall', 'energy', 'consumption', 'predicted', 'greenhouse', 'gas', 'emissions', 'reduced', 'electricity', 'generated', 'little', 'fossil', 'fuels', 'authors']"
16,0,0,"Emissions scenarios used by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) are based on detailed energy system models in which demographics, technology and economics are used to generate projections of future world energy consumption, and therefore, of greenhouse gas emissions. We propose in this paper that it is useful to look at a qualitative model of the energy system, backed by data from short- and medium-term trends, to gain a sense of carbon emission bounds. Here we look at what may be considered a lower bound for 21st century emissions given two assumptions: first, that extractable fossil-fuel resources follow the trends assumed by 'peak oil' adherents, and second, that no climate mitigation policies are put in place to limit emissions. If resources, and more importantly, extraction rates, of fossil fuels are more limited than posited in full energy-system models, a supply-driven emissions scenario results; however, we show that even in this 'peak fossil-fuel' limit, carbon emissions are high enough to surpass 550 ppm or 2 °C climate protection guardrails. Some indicators are presented that the scenario presented here should not be disregarded, and comparisons are made to the outputs of emission scenarios used for the IPCC reports. © 2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","['emissions', 'scenarios', 'used', 'intergovernmental', 'panel', 'climate', 'change', 'ipcc', 'detailed', 'energy', 'system', 'models', 'demographics', 'technology', 'economics', 'used', 'generate', 'projections', 'future', 'world', 'energy', 'consumption', 'greenhouse', 'gas', 'emissions', 'propose', 'useful', 'qualitative', 'model', 'energy', 'system', 'backed', 'data', 'short', 'medium', 'term', 'trends', 'gain', 'sense', 'carbon', 'emission', 'bounds', 'considered', 'lower', 'bound', 'century', 'emissions', 'given', 'assumptions', 'extractable', 'fossil', 'fuel', 'resources', 'follow', 'trends', 'assumed', 'adherents', 'second', 'climate', 'mitigation', 'policies', 'put'